Despite the difficulty in writing them so that they don't sound stupid, I enjoy  as a genre. This is a good entry into that realm. The anomaly is suitably unsettling without getting into narmy attempts to spook, and despite my increasing dissatisfaction with the interview as an exposition device in general, this was done in a satisfactory manner here.

Two nitpicks. I'm not sure it's necessary to specifically mention that it lacks a compulsion effect; out-of-universe I can see why you went out of your way to mention it, but in-universe I'm not sure why that would be specifically noted. And like other posters, I have a little difficulty reading some of the longer dialogue images.

Nice article.







